RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Deprecation
<hw>Dep`re*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(d⟦ecr⟧p`r⟦esl⟧*k⟦amac⟧"sh⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>deprecatio</ets>; cf. F.
<ets>d⟦eacute⟧pr⟦eacute⟧cation</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
deprecating; a praying against evil; prayer that an evil may be removed
or prevented.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark> ⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Humble <qex>deprecation</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Entreaty for pardon; petitioning.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An imprecation or curse.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Gilpin.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A strong expression of disapprobation; an expression
of a low opinion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Deprecative</ent>⟦br⟧
